July 19, 2017 (RADIO KIRIBATI) ---- More than 100 dolphins landed on the lagoon shores of Kabuna village on the island of Tabiteuea North in the Southern Gilberts after the construction of the village’s maneaba ‘Bibitoinikarawa’ was complete.

Resident of the village Tabukinikai Tabwanou told Radio Kiribati News the incident occurred between 10am and 12pm on Tuesday.

Tabukinikai says the incident is not something new to the village because it has been happening over the past years.

He says whenever a new ‘maneaba’ for the village is constructed or renovated, scores of dolphins will be seen swimming towards the shore and just stayed there...RK News

behavior: Was seen by local villagers swimming in the lagoon for the 2 days prior to the stranding
Remarks:
The villagers reported the whale was seen on both the 2 days prior to the stranding in the lagoon. They said the villagers who were out in the canoe found it was dead on Sunday morning and towed it to the beach. The site where it ’stranded' is was is a shallow lagoon with mangroves and seagrass. There was apparently not any fishing gear or any other evidence of entanglement.

Skin had multiple abrasions but it is unclear if occurred whilst it was towed to shore or before.

Carcass had been dismembered before fisheries officers started examination – head, fins and tail had been removed therefore morphological measurements and whole body head and dorsal fin photos could not be obtained.

No obvious cause of death was apparent at the time of the post mortem but the body had been dismembered by this time. The carcass was fresh and therefore consistent with the reports it was alive the day before.

Post Mortem observations: There was no froth or fluid in the lungs or airways. Drowning is usually associated with froth in the airways so it is unlikely to have drowned. Stomach was empty. Other internal organs appeared grossly normal.

Hi all,

Hope this finds you well. A dead sperm whale was washed ashore on Niue last Tuesday. I've attached some photos for you. I've taken a skin sample, a tissue sample and a tooth. If you could let me know how you want me to store these and what you'd like me to do or arrange to have them sent somewhere or even just disposed that would be great.
The whale is located at Kavata in Hikutavake. Happz - the carcass might still be there by the time you come if you want to go down and have a look.

Email me soon as possible as what you'd like done with those samples. There's been too much exposure to the sun and its exterior has deteriorated significantly. Can't really tell what other signs there might be - just squid bite marks.

Best,
Ness

On February 18, 2012, Joe Katangi found a dead and decomposing whale lodged on a coral head in the Aitutaki lagoon at S 18’ 53.956’, W 159’ 48.933, approximately 4.2 km south of the Arutanga wharf. Nan Hauser and team pulled the dead carcass out of Aitutaki Lagoon on February 21st, 2012 (an 8 hour ordeal) and left it floating approximately 5 miles outside the harbour. (At the request of the Island council). A section of sample tissue was taken from the tail and frozen. Three additional tissue samples were stored in 3% gluteraldahyde, 0.9% ammonium formate filtered to 0.2 µm, and high concentration NaCl, respectively. One tooth ~ 5 cm and a small section of bone were recovered. All whale samples were stored at the Aitutaki Marine Research Centre (AMRC). There are also skin and blubber samples in Rarotonga.

verbatimLocality: Te Uki Ou school. Cook Islands reef
behavior: Stranded alive. Cut up. Lower jaw smashed on reef. Approximately 3 inches of lower rostrum broken off. Otherwise healthy looking animal. No signs of emaciation or cause of death.
Remarks:
Kakera appeared in shallow water early in the morning after washing over the reef just outside of Te Uki Ou School. She died shortly afterwards. She had eaten so recently that during her immediate necropsy, there was actually something in her stomach that still was wiggling around!
Head and brain necropsied separately at a later date by Darlene Ketten and Nan Hauser. Brain, eyes, ears, and mandibular fats sent to Woods Hole Oceanographic Institute.

Temata, stranded alive after being washed over reef, listing when released. Weak, confused, dehydrated. Tried 2x to release in deep water after moving on trailer to Avatiu Harbour. brought to wharf and died 36 hours later.

Four animals, including three males and one female, were found dead, and morphometrics, including dental counts, were collected. Two live mature males of 236 and 246cm total length, respectively, were closely monitored and sampled via blood analysis. As it was not likely to survive, the second animal was euthanised and necropsied. Following the euthanasia of the larger animal, the smaller one, which was probably staying out of social solidarity, returned on its own to the open sea.

Clua, E. E., C. A. Manire, and C. Garrigue. 2014. Biological data of pygmy killer whale (Feresa attenuata) from a mass stranding in New Caledonia (South Pacific) associated with Hurricane Jim in 2006. Aquatic Mammals 40:DOI 10.1578/AM.1540.1572.2014.
